T1  - Militarism and Political Conformism in Sudan and South Sudan
AN  - 2491200833
AB  - The culture of political conformity and arbitrary sociopolitical contracts within Sudan and South Sudan were influenced by colonialist-engineered politics of divide and rule, which were later adopted by the post-independence Sudanese political elites. It has resulted in two bloody civil wars (1955-1972, 1983-2005) that ended with the signing of Comprehensive Peace Agreement (CPA) and the separation of South Sudan in 2011. It is now evident, however, that the separation of South Sudan did not address issues of political stability, and economic and institutional development, or set the stage for political reforms in these two countries. At its core, unresolved political grievances between politically and economically marginalized groups in the peripheral areas of these countries and their unelected military political elites has undermined the quest for sustainable social, economic, and political progress. Hence, the two nations continue to endure challenges derived from decades of armed conflicts tainted by unresolved ethnic, regional, and political grievances. That lack of political will in conflict resolution, transition to democracy, and equitable power sharing, has delayed all aspects of sustainable economic development projects, thereby fueling political unrest and instabilities.
